  "body": "Hi, I met some problem with event handler binding in React ES6 class syntax\n\n``` javascript\n// Render() of parent component\nrender() {\n        const { trades, contracts } = this.props;\n        const allID = Object.keys(trades);\n        return (\n            <div>\n                {allID.map(id => {\n                        return (\n                            <TradePanel\n                                key={id}\n                                id={id}\n                                {...this.props}\n                            />\n                        );\n                    }\n                })}\n            </div>\n        );\n\n// child Component class\nclass TradePanel extends Component {\n        method1(e) {\n                const { id } = this.props;\n                ....\n        }\n\n        render() {\n                return <input onChange={::this.method1} />\n        }\n}\n```\n\nProblem happens when I create 2nd instance of child component, method1 is incorrectly bounded to `this` of 1st instance.\n\nOther props are pass properly, the problems are with event handlers.\n\nWhen render() is called, will the binding be re-evaluate? \nIf parent component rerender, does it destroy the old children and reconstruct a new one ?\n\nRegards ~\n",
